    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nCurrently, [`resolve_lang`](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/a8361c3afc5b9281814e9f16a9d4291e095b38fa/runtime/lua/vim/treesitter/languagetree.lua#L1025-L1028) validates injection language names against the pattern `[%w_]+`, which rejects any name containing a hyphen.\n\nThis silently drops injections for a large number of language identifiers that are in widespread use. For example, in a Markdown fenced code block:\n\n````\n```shell-session\n$ go build ./...\n```\n````\n\nEven with `vim.treesitter.language.register('bash', 'shell-session')` configured, the injection never fires because `resolve_lang` returns nil before ever consulting the registration table.\n\nHyphenated identifiers are standard across major tools:\n\n- [Prism.js](https://github.com/PrismJS/prism/tree/master/components): shell-session, css-extras, go-module, firestore-security-rules, web-idl, visual-basic, etc.\n- [Shiki](https://shiki.style/languages): actionscript-3, common-lisp, emacs-lisp, git-commit, git-rebase, objective-c, ssh-config, system-verilog, etc.\n- [GitHub Linguist](https://github.com/github-linguist/linguist/blob/main/lib/linguist/languages.yml): Objective-C, CoNLL-U, ssh-config, Tree-sitter Query, etc.\n\nThe fix would be to either:\n1. Widen the pattern to allow hyphens: `[%w_-]+`\n2. Normalize hyphens to underscores before validation and lookup, so shell-session resolves the same as shell_session\n\nOption 2 would also align with how vim.filetype handles extension matching.\n\nRelates to #27080.\n\nHappy to open a PR for this, just wanted to get feedback on if this is feasible / which approach would be preferred.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n```\nvim.treesitter.language.register('bash', 'shell-session')\n```\n\n...\n\nopen markdown file with:\n\n````\n```shell-session\n$ go build ./...\n```\n````\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nI expect `shell-session` to get `bash` injected syntax highlighting.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\n0.11.6\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nn/a\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nmacOS 26.3\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nghostty 1.2.3\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-ghostty\n\n### Installation\n\nhomebrew",
